metadata.name: Obliques #28
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #59
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: YANF #53
metadata.description:
Yet Another Noises and Flows

After three works on landscapes I returned to an abstract work in which I used several kinds of noise fields and a different approach to flow lines.

In this work I use three intermediate images to generate the final image:
- on the first image to each pixels is assigned a color related to the value of the noise field in that point using the main color palette
- on the second image the gradient orientation (angle) of the field is used to assign colors using a secondary palette with the purpose of giving lights and shadows to the final image
- on the third image flow lines are drawn using the direction perpendicular to the gradient, in this way the flows are aligned to the contour lines

After the second and third step the new generated image is blended with the previous giving rise to the final image.

Developed with p5.js

Default resolution: 2400x1600, 1600x2400, 2000x2000 (3/2, 2/3, 1/1 aspect ratio)

[2] to redraw at double resolution (it takes four times then default)
[1] to redraw at default resolution
[s] to save a png at current resolution

Sources of variations are:
- 14 palettes
- 6 kinds of combinations of noise type and fractal type
- 8 kinds of cuts
- 3 kinds of aspect ratio
- 3 border thickness

This Generative Token uses the FastNoiseLite.js and chroma.js libraries.

Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Kaibō #138
metadata.description:
What would happen if we took the natural forms that surround us and dissected them into composable shapes? 

Taking the organic world of Yashinoki, Kiabō dissects organic forms into composable elements, then reforms them into precise geometric arrangements. These shapes give way to random, organic growth the closer we look at them. 


Controls in live mode:
- Press [s] to save a png

Made with code by AutoEclectus.
 AutoEclectus is an artist specialising in code-based generative works.
